pub fn isIsogram(str: []const u8) bool {
    var seen: u32 = 0;
    const n = str.len;
    for (i in 0..n) {
        const c = str[i];
        // check if letter
        const lower = if (c >= 'A' and c <= 'Z') {
            @intCast(c) + 32 // to lowercase
        } else if (c >= 'a' and c <= 'z') {
            @intCast(c)
        } else {
            // not a letter, skip
            continue;
        }
        const idx = lower - 'a';
        const mask = 1u32 << idx;
        if (seen and mask) != 0 {
            return false;
        }
        seen |= mask;
    }
    return true;
}

Need to ensure that subtraction 'a' works: lower is u8, 'a' is u8. In Zig, char literals are u8. So lower - 'a' yields u8. But we need to cast to u32 for shift? We can do: const idx = lower - 'a'; // u8
then mask = 1u32 << idx; but shift expects integer type same as shift? In Zig, shift operators work on usize, i32, etc. 1u32 << idx where idx is u8 will be promoted to u32. That's fine.

But need to ensure that idx < 32, which is true for a-z.

Potential overflow if idx >= 32 (e.g., non-ASCII). But we only consider a-z.

Edge Cases: The string may contain characters outside ASCII; but tests only ASCII.

Now ensure function signature matches: pub fn isIsogram(str: []const u8) bool

Implementation uses const, no allocator.

